Lab 4¶

In this lab we will be exploring how to determine what type of distribution best fits our raw data

Problem 1: Cosmic Background Radiation¶

In this problem we will be considering simulated data from a gamma-ray satellite orbiting Earth in low orbit. While it is looking for Gamma-Ray Bursts, a majority of the data it collects are cosmic rays--that is, the cosmic rays appear as our background.

The satellite takes a reading every 100 milliseconds and its orbit is 90 minutes long. Hence we have 54,000 measurments per orbit (of the satellite around Earth).

Our data consists of 25,920,001 different readings, hence we have data collected over 480 orbits of the satellite around Earth.

Our data consists of 4 columns, listed in order: Time (GPS sec), Solar Phase (deg), Earth Longitude (deg), Particle Counts.

We want to explore what our background of cosmic rays looks like.

1.1 Varies with Longitude¶

Our first step is to make a plot of the total number of counts as a function of time. When we try to plot all of the data at once it is hard to see any features since there is so much data.

In [140]:
figure(figsize = (20,4))
plt.title('Counts vs. Time')
plt.xlabel('Time (GPS Seconds)')
plt.ylabel('Counts')
plt.plot(time,counts)
plt.show()

So we must decide on a suitable range to look at so that we might see any features that arise in our background.

Since we know our satellite is physically orbiting around Earth, we expect to see a periodicity on the scale of 90 minutes. Hence we need to make sure we plot data that includes at least one full orbit's worth of measurements. We would like to see if there are 'slower' features than the periodicity caused by the 90-minute orbit, so we should actually plot multiple orbits' worth of data.

Recall that 1 orbit = 54,000 measurements. Below we plot data collected over five orbits

We see that there is in fact a periodicity to our background data as we include multiple orbits. In fact, the period appears to be around 5,400 seconds = 90 minutes. Let's make a plot of how the longitude varies with time and overlay this onto our data so we can see if there is indeed a correlation:

Note that for easy comparison we have rescaled the longitude by 1/350, and the counts by 1/30. we see that the periodicity of our count data seems to be well-correlated with the longitudinal position of the satellite. That is, the background is not constant simply because the satellite is orbiting the earth and hence looking at different portions of space as it orbits.

We still cannot say anything about signal contamination; since our background varies with longitude (or, equivalently, with time), we must first determine what our background looks like as a function of where the satellite is in space so that we can then determine from a localized distribution whether or not a measurement is likely to be a signal.

Before we delve into using longitudnal data to help us look at our background, let's take a quick look at how the background varies with solar phase:

1.2 How Background Varies Longitudinally¶

Since we can look at our data as counting rays within a longitudinal interval we expect our distribution for the average number of counts in a given region of space to be Poisson Distributed. Below we plot the histograms for the average counts in different longitudinal intervals: 1 orbit, 1/2 orbit, 1/4 orbit, 1/8 orbit, and 1/16 orbit.

In [191]:

averageover = 54000 #average over 1 orbit = 54000 measurements

j = 0
while j < 480:
    sumvar = 0
    for i in range(j*54000,(j+1)*54000):
        sumvar = sumvar + counts[i]

    average1orbit = sumvar/54000
    averagearray = np.append(averagearray,[average1orbit])
    j = j+1

plt.show()

We see that as we average over smaller spatial intervals we get more and more distinct peaks that appear to be poisson distributed. In Figure 12 We have plotted the log scale of Figure 11 to see that each distribution indeed resembles a discrete version of a negative quadratic which is indicative of Poisson Distributions.

Hence, we conclude that our background is a Poisson Distribution whose average varies with longitude. That is:

$$ f(l) = \frac{\mu(l)}{k!} e^{-\mu(l)},$$

where the average $\mu(l)$ is a function of longitude, $l$, (or alternatively can be transformed to a function of time). note that the above plot does not plot counts as a function of longitude; rather distinct peaks appear because each longitudinal segment will produce a new poisson distribution. We check our hypothesis in the next two figures.

Below we calculate the histogram over each 1/16 orbit and then calculate the mean of the histogram to find where our Poisson distributions are centered. To further convince ourselves that a Poisson is a good local model of our data, we also display an overlayed Poisson distribution over what we expect the first two distributions in Figure 11 to be.

In [88]:
def poisson16orbit(interval):
    min = interval*3375
    max = min + 3375
    
    batch = np.array([])
    while max <= 25920000:
        sumvar = 0
        for i in range(min,max):
            sumvar = sumvar + counts[i]
        
        
        batch = np.append(batch,[sumvar])
        min = min+54000
        max = max+54000 #move to next orbit
        
    return(batch)

1.3 Sensitivity Threshold¶

Since our Poisson average decreases from our selected 'start point' as the satellite orbits Earth, *our sensitivity threshold also decreases since we define our signal-like measurements to be large counts.

2.1 Determining Background¶

Before we can look for a signal, we need to decide what our background looks like. Since our signal is transient objects -- objects that appear in only one image -- we may virtually eliminate these signals by averaging all of our images together. Objects that are persistent--appear in nearly all 10 images--will have an average brightness that is close to the brightness in each individual picture.

However, objects that appear only once will have an average brightness that is 1/10th of the brightness that appears in that one image.

Hence if we make a histogram of the average brightnesses in the averaged picture, we will essentially be ignoring the transient signal; we can then histogram each picture individually to identify where a possible signal might be, and use our averaged background to determine the significance.
